\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 1.               Fagus}                 L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †T.G. Tutin (Ed.1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd (Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Deciduous trees. Buds fusiform. Flowers anemophilous. Male flowers in long-pedunculate, pendent heads; perianth 4- to 7-lobed; stamens 8-16. Female flowers usually in pairs in each stipitate, 4-partite cupule; perianth 4- or 5-lobed; styles 3, elongate. Nuts 1 or 2, triquetrous.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. F. sylvatica} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 998 (1753). Tree up to 40 m; bark grey, smooth. Buds acute, reddish-brown. Leaves 4-9 cm, ovate-elliptic, acute, ciliate and silky, at least on the veins. Male flowers numerous; peduncles 5-6 cm. Nut 12-18 mm, brown; cupule c. 2·5 cm. {\i Forming woods, usually on well-drained soils, often on mountains in the south; widely planted elsewhere. S.W. &
\pard\f0\fs28  C. Europe, extending to S. Sweden.} Al Au Be Br Bu Co Cz Da Ga Ge Gr He Ho Hs Hu It Ju No Po Rm Rs(B, W, K, E) Si Su Tu [Hb].
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  sylvatica} : Tree up to 30 m. Leaves 4-9 cm, with 5-8 pairs of veins. Perianth of male flowers divided almost to base. Cupule with all scales subulate. 2n = 24.{\i  Almost throughout the range of the species}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b orientalis} (Lipsky) Greuter & Burdet,{\i  Willdenowia}{\b  11:} 279 (1981) ({\i F. orientalis} Lipsky); Tree up to 40 m. Leaves 9-12(-14) cm, with 8-12 pairs of lateral veins. Perianth of male flowers divided for not more than 1/3 of its length. Cupule with linear-oblong scales above and spathulate scales below.{\i  At lower elevations and in more sheltered sites than subsp.} ({\b a}).{\i  S.E. Europe from C. Greece to S.E. Russia.}
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Plants intermediate between subspp. ({\b a}) and ({\b b}) that occur in E., E.C. and S.E. Europe have been described as species under the names {\b F. taurica} Popl., {\i Österr. Bot. Zeitschr.}{\b  77:} 41 (1928), and {\b F. moesiaca }(K. Malý) Czech., {\i Annu. Soc. Dendrol. Pologne}{\b  5:} 52 (1933).
